<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="111" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="111">Habitat and range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="111">
Open upland forests, mountain steppe, generally in light, well-drained soils to somewhat heavy soils. Range of the subspecies (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of Poa secunda subspecies in North America: subsp. secunda (yellow); subsp. juncifolia (blue)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.110.27750.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/240277" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">2B</figureCitation>
), but mostly absent from west side of the Sierra Nevada and westwards. Minor outlying occurrences in Arizona and New Mexico of subsp. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" subspecies="juncifolia">juncifolia</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of Poa secunda subspecies in North America: subsp. secunda (yellow); subsp. juncifolia (blue)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.110.27750.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/240277" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">2B</figureCitation>
) mostly represent var. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="var. ampla" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="variety" species="truncata" variety="ampla">ampla</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Soreng, RJ" journalOrPublisher="The Great Basin Naturalist" pageId="16" pageNumber="117" pagination="395 - 422" refId="B31" refString="Soreng, RJ, 1985. Poa in New Mexico, with a key to middle and southern Rocky Mountain species (Poaceae). The Great Basin Naturalist 45: 395 - 422" title="Poa in New Mexico, with a key to middle and southern Rocky Mountain species (Poaceae)." volume="45" year="1985">Soreng 1985</bibRefCitation>
), likely introduced by seeding.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
